{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518146"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:01:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:01:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12889"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12889"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.81,0.01,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5330"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38784"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5330"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12889"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23129"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"145"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9058"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9627"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38784"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman is in active labour at 38 weeks gestation on a background of poorly controlled gestational diabetes. She is having difficulty delivering the foetal shoulders after the head has been delivered. The anterior shoulder remains stuck behind the pubic symphysis. The midwives recognise this is a  shoulder dystocia and has pressed the emergency button for immediate assistance. The obstetric team are on their way.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following methods should be the initial step in managing this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Suprapubic pressure","McRoberts manoeuvre","Rubin manoeuvre","Woods corkscrew manoeuvre","Zavanelli manoeuvre"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EShoulder dystocia is an obstetric emergency during which the shoulder of the foetus becomes impacted behind the maternal symphysis pubic, or less commonly, the maternal sacral promontory. It is caused by a disproportion between the foetal bisacromial diameter and the dorsoventral diameter of the pelvic inlet. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of shoulder dystocia may be summarised with the \u003Cstrong\u003EHELPERR\u003C/strong\u003E mnemonic, however, keep in mind that not all manoeuvres need to be carried out sequentially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EH: call for \u003Cstrong\u003EH\u003C/strong\u003Eelp\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EE: \u003Cstrong\u003EE\u003C/strong\u003Evaluate for \u003Cstrong\u003EE\u003C/strong\u003Episiotomy\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EL: \u003Cstrong\u003EL\u003C/strong\u003Eegs: McRoberts manoeuvre\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EP: \u003Cstrong\u003EP\u003C/strong\u003Eressure externally - suprapubic\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EE:\u003Cstrong\u003E E\u003C/strong\u003Enter rotational manoeuvres\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ER: \u003Cstrong\u003ER\u003C/strong\u003Eemove the posterior arm \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ER: \u003Cstrong\u003ER\u003C/strong\u003Eoll the patient to her hands and knees \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMcRoberts manoeuvre\u003C/strong\u003E is the initial step in managing shoulder dystocia. It involves flexing the woman\u0027s thighs against her abdomen to increase the pelvic angle and open the space between the pubic symphysis and the foetal shoulder. This manoeuvre helps release the impacted shoulder and facilitate successful delivery of the baby in \u0026gt;50% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuprapubic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E involves applying pressure above the pubic bone in an attempt to dislodge the anterior shoulder. While it can be used as an adjunctive manoeuvre, it is recommended after the McRoberts manoeuvre has failed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERubin manoeuvre\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as the posterior axilla sling manoeuvre, involves rotating the baby\u0027s anterior shoulder toward the mother\u0027s back. It is used as a secondary manoeuvre after the initial steps, such as the McRoberts manoeuvre, have been performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWoods corkscrew manoeuvre\u003C/strong\u003E is a rotational manoeuvre used to release the impacted shoulder. It involves rotating the baby\u0027s posterior shoulder in a corkscrew-like motion to dislodge it from behind the pubic symphysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZavanelli manoeuvre\u003C/strong\u003E involves pushing the foetal head back into the birth canal and performing an emergency caesarean section. It is a last-resort measure when all other manoeuvres fail.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The McRoberts manoeuvre is first line management for shoulder dystocia"],"references":["Shoulder Dystocia. Green top Guideline No.42 (2012). https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/shoulder-dystocia-green-top-guideline-no-42/","Prompt Shoulder Dystocia Training. Accessed 08/08/2023. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UTz2eIiZOL8","Khan, L (2019). Shoulder Dystocia. TeachMe ObGyn Accessed 08/08/2023. https://teachmeobgyn.com/labour/emergencies/shoulder-dystocia/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23129"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12889"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/23129"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-08-08T18:48:45+09:30","up